<h2>HVAC Systems in Colorado</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Colorado's diverse climate zones present unique challenges for HVAC system design and operation, requiring equipment that can efficiently handle both heating and cooling demands across extreme temperature variations. The state encompasses five distinct climate zones, from the semi-arid steppe climate of the eastern plains to the alpine tundra of the high Rockies. Most populated areas experience a continental semi-arid climate characterized by low humidity, significant daily temperature swings, and substantial seasonal variations. Denver, for example, sees average winter lows of 15¬∞F and summer highs of 89¬∞F, with occasional temperature swings of 40-50 degrees in a single day.</p>

<p>The heating season typically extends from October through April, requiring approximately 6,100 heating degree days annually in the Denver metro area, while cooling needs are more modest at around 700-900 cooling degree days. This heating-dominant climate favors heat pump systems, particularly cold-climate air-source heat pumps that maintain efficiency at temperatures well below freezing. The low humidity levels, often dropping below 20% in winter, necessitate integrated humidification systems to maintain indoor comfort and protect wooden furnishings and musical instruments.</p>

<p>High altitude locations face additional challenges including reduced air density, which affects equipment sizing calculations and combustion appliance performance. Gas furnaces and boilers require altitude adjustments above 2,000 feet elevation to maintain proper air-fuel ratios and prevent incomplete combustion. Air-source heat pumps benefit from the thinner air that reduces system pressure drops, but sizing must account for the reduced heating capacity at extreme low temperatures common in mountain communities.</p>

